ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="Now I have a thorough understanding of the code changes. Let me analy
ze each file for issues.\n\n1. **BuildingDetailPanel.ts**: Looks clean. Good use
of new UI components. One potential issue: `getBuildingEffect` uses hardcoded bu
ilding IDs and effects - this is business logic hardcoded in UI, but it was alre
ady there before. No new issues introduced. The `updateUpgradeCost` also has har
dcoded baseCost = 100.\n\n2. **BuildingSelector.ts**: Clean. Good migration to U
IList/UIPanel. One thing: it lost the building icons (emoji) that were previousl
y displayed. The old code had `getBuildingIcon` with emojis for each building. T
he new UIList just shows label with name and dimensions. This is a functional/UI
regression, though possibly intentional per PRD-005.\n\n3. **ConfirmationDialog.
ts**: Clean wrapper around UIDialog. The `show()` method notes that UIDialog doe
sn't support dynamic title/message updates - this is a known limitation document
ed in a comment. The `confirmColor` config is accepted but not passed to UIDialo
g (ignored). This is a minor API regression but the class is marked `@deprecated
` anyway.\n\n4. **RemoveConfirmDialog.ts**: Clean. Good use of UIPanel. One issu
e: `destroy()` calls `this.panel?.destroy()` but `super.destroy()` should handle
the container's children. Calling `panel.destroy()` might double-destroy or caus
e issues if panel is already being destroyed by the container. Actually in Phase
r, when a Container is destroyed, its children are destroyed too (by default, wi
th `destroyChildren = true`). So explicit `this.panel?.destroy()` is redundant a
nd potentially risky. Same issue in UpgradeConfirmDialog.\n\n5. **TopInfoBar.ts*
*: Clean. Good migration. The resource icons were changed from emoji-based `labe
l` to `UIIcon` components, but UIIcon doesn't seem to receive any actual icon/te
xture key - it just gets `size`, `fallbackColor`, `strokeColor`. Looking at the 
old code, it had emojis like `💰`, `🪵`, `⛏️`, `👷`. The new code uses `UIIcon` w
ithout specifying what icon to show. This is likely a functional regression - th
e icons won't display properly.\n\nWait, let me check the UIIcon implementation 
to see if there's a `textureKey` or `icon` parameter I'm missing.",
    encrypted=None
)
